---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Problem of Tolerance | Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The moral and economic foundations of the Theory of Minimal Tolerance"
    />

    <link
      rel="canonical"
      href="https://minimaltolerance.com/theory/"
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>

      <!-- PAGE TITLE -->

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THEORY
          </p>

          <h1>
            The problem of tolerance
          </h1>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- OPENING STATEMENT -->

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The State does not become legitimate.
          At most, it may be tolerated
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <!-- MORAL PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE MORAL PROBLEM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Political authority rests on coercion
          </h2>

        <p>
        The State is routinely exempted from principles that govern every other human relationship. Consent is treated as essential in private interactions but becomes secondary once political authority enters the picture
        </p>

        <p>
        The relationship between the individual and the State is neither voluntary nor optional. Disagreement does not eliminate the obligation to comply, nor does it release individuals from rules imposed without their personal agreement
        </p>

        <p>
        The ability to impose a decision does not establish a right to impose it. Coercion may secure compliance, but compliance and legitimacy are not the same thing
        </p>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- EFFICIENCY PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

         <p class="eyebrow">
  THE EFFICIENCY PROBLEM
</p>

<h2>
  Why centralized decisions fail
</h2>

<p>
  The knowledge required to coordinate a complex society
  is dispersed among millions of individuals. No planner
  can know what millions of people know about their own
  circumstances
</p>

<p>
  Prices communicate information about scarcity,
  preferences and opportunity costs. They allow
  individuals to coordinate their decisions without
  requiring a central authority to direct the process
</p>

<p>
  The State replaces decentralized choices with political
  direction while operating with less information, weaker
  feedback and fewer mechanisms for correcting error
</p>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- MARKET FAILURE -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            MARKET FAILURE
          </p>

          <h2>
            A misleading justification
          </h2>

          <p>
            Market failure is often presented as sufficient reason
            for state intervention. Friction, externalities,
            incomplete information or an undesirable result are
            treated as proof that coercion will produce something
            better
          </p>

          <p>
            That comparison places an imperfect market against an
            ideal government. Real political institutions also
            operate with incomplete information, distorted
            incentives and weak feedback
          </p>

          <p>
            Markets adapt through agreements, prices, innovation,
            reputation and changes in property rights. The State
            does not eliminate imperfection. It replaces voluntary
            correction with compulsory decisions whose costs are
            imposed on others
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- SECOND STATEMENT -->

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The existence of a social problem does not justify
          coercion
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <!-- STRUCTURAL FREE RIDER -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            NOT A MARKET FAILURE
          </p>

          <h2>
            A structural free-rider problem
          </h2>

          <p>
            Minimal Tolerance addresses a narrower problem.
            Individuals may receive a benefit whether or not they
            contribute to its provision. The incentive to withhold
            payment grows when others cannot exclude them from that
            benefit
          </p>

          <p>
            A structural free-rider problem exists when voluntary
            provision collapses persistently because of the
            incentive structure itself.
          </p>

          <p>
            This does not create legitimacy. It identifies a
            practical limit that a theory based on voluntary
            relations cannot ignore
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- LEGITIMACY AND TOLERANCE -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            LEGITIMACY AND TOLERANCE
          </p>

          <h2>
            Necessity does not create legitimacy
          </h2>

          <p>
            A practical limit does not create a moral right to
            coerce. Coercion remains illegitimate regardless of the
            purpose it claims to serve
          </p>

          <p>
            Minimal Tolerance separates moral judgment from
            practical acceptance. The State is never legitimized.
            Its limited use may be tolerated only as an exceptional
            response to a real institutional constraint
          </p>

          <p>
            Tolerance is not approval. It marks the boundary of a
            reluctant exception.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- LINK TO THEOREM -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THEOREM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Defining the boundary
          </h2>

          <p>
            The theorem defines when that narrow exception may be
            considered.
          </p>

          <div class="buttons">

            <a href="/theorem/" class="primary">
              Read the Theorem
            </a>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
